You said:
I would like to build the app using TypeScript and VUES. These applications I need is actually a template. Each component I need to use it with any project I need. So, in that case, what files should I transfer to the main project, to the main big project. And every time I use npm to create environment or how it works without giving me any code.
ChatGPT said:

Great! It sounds like you're building a reusable component library in TypeScript + Vue (I assume you meant Vue 3), and want to use it as a template or base for other projects.

Here’s how it works conceptually, step-by-step, without code:

1. Create a Component Library

You should start by setting up a standalone Vue + TypeScript project that only contains reusable components (your template).

This project includes:

  • Your reusable components

  • TypeScript types/interfaces

  • SCSS/CSS (if any)

  • Any shared composables or utilities

This becomes your component library.

2. Build the Library

Instead of using npm create for every new project, you'll use a build tool (like Vite or Rollup) in your component library to bundle the components into reusable modules (usually CommonJS or ESM).

3. Publish or Link Your Library

You have two options to use the components in other projects:

Option A: Publish it

  • Publish your component library to npm (private or public).

  • Then in any project, you just npm install your-library.

Option B: Local linking

  • Use npm link or a local file path (e.g., npm install ../my-component-library) in other projects.

4. Using in Main Project

In your big project, you:

  • Install the component library (published or local).

  • Import and use components as needed.

You do not copy files manually. You only import components from your library like any npm package.

5. Only Create Environment Once

You create the environment (i.e., using npm init, setting up Vite, etc.) once for your library and once for each app that will use it.

You do not repeat this every time unless you're starting a completely new app.

Let me know if you want help choosing the best structure or build setup. I can also walk you through publishing or using local linking when you're ready.
